{
  "texts": [
    "Even though these are relevant concerns, they nonetheless represent a quite limited set of impacts that, by focusing on issues that can be technically fixed, can leave unchecked relevant structural injustices underpinning the AI industry (Attard-Frost and Widder 2023; Ricaurte 2022; Bender et al. 2021; Powell et al. 2022; Rességuier and Rodrigues 2020).",
    "As a consequence, questions over 'the wider contexts and the comprehensive relationship networks in which technical systems are embedded' (Hagendorff 2020, p. 103) have remained in the background.",
    "In fact, even well-intentioned 'AI for good' initiatives have been proven to yield short-term benefits at the expense of the root causes underlying social and environmental injustices (Aula and Bowles 2023; Madianou 2020).",
    "The same lack of attention to both structural asymmetries and AI's value chain has also permeated the influential 'AI safety' agenda revolving around hypothetical cases of 'rogue AI', namely robots surpassing human intelligence and acting autonomously, posing existential threats (Hendrycks et al. 2023).",
    "Crucial in this regard have been ideologies circulating in the centres of AI development in the United States such as long-termism and effective altruism that have provided an excuse for an elite to impose their own priorities to the detriment of the concerns held by a broad range of other actors affected by AI (Gebru and Torres 2023; Kaspersen and Wallach 2022)."
  ]
}